<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06111131 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06111131 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  VATICAN-CITY; ECONOMY; REPORT; BUDGET  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  ONLY days after the world's bishops agreed to help the pope cover the church'sgrowing money woes, officials announced that the 1991 Vatican deficit isexpected to reach a record $91.5 million.;    The Vatican expects revenues forthe year to be $76.7 million, contrasted with estimated expenses of $168.1million.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Religion andamp; Ethics  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  VATICAN REPORTS DEFICIT AT RECORD $91.5 MILLION  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Catholics  </MEMO><TEXT>     The figures were issued in connection with a meeting earlier this month atthe Vatican of the Council of 15 Cardinals established by Pope John Paul II tostudy organizational and financial reforms of the Holy See.;    The reportconveyed at least one piece of good news. The Peter's Pence annual collectionto the pope from Catholics throughout the world in 1990 rose by 19 percent to$58 million.;    The estimated Vatican deficit for 1990, also a record, is $86million.;    In the past, the pope has covered the budget deficit with thePeter's Pence and other offerings made to him for his personal use.;    Butnow, the presidents of all 101 bishops' conferences agreed to the pope'srequest that they take on the deficit so that he can use the offerings forsuch special purposes as helping the church in Eastern Europe.;    The bishopshave not disclosed how they will go about raising the funds from the 2,700Roman Catholic dioceses worldwide.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Religious News Service  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Vatican City  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910420  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  11C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  214  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday April 20, 199100111131,